Based on the search results, here's comprehensive information about Tailwind CSS v4's `@theme` directive for customizing colors and fonts:

## Tailwind CSS v4 @theme Directive

Theme variables are special CSS variables defined using the @theme directive that influence which utility classes exist in your project.

### CSS-First Configuration

Instead of a tailwind.config.js file, you can configure all of your customizations directly in the CSS file where you import Tailwind, including configuring your design tokens, defining custom utilities and variants, and more.

### Custom Colors

You can add custom colors to your project using the `@theme` directive. Utilities like bg-midnight, text-tahiti, and fill-bermuda will be available in your project in addition to the default colors.

For example:
```css
@import "tailwindcss";
@theme {
  --color-midnight: #121063;
  --color-tahiti: #3ab7bf;
  --color-bermuda: #78dcca;
}
```

### Custom Fonts

Theme variables defined in the --font-* namespace determine all of the font-family utilities that exist in a project. You can add custom fonts like:

```css
@theme {
  --font-display: "Satoshi", "sans-serif";
}
```

### Overriding Default Theme

To completely override an entire namespace in the default theme, set the entire namespace to initial using the special asterisk syntax, which will remove all of the default utilities that use that namespace, and only your custom values will be available.


